Preheat your #oven{} to 200C. Halve, peel and thinly slice the @onion{1}(halved and thinly sliced). Trim the @butternut squash{1} then halve lengthways and scoop out the seeds. Chop it widthways into 1cm slices, then chop into 1cm chunks (no need to peel!) Peel and grate the @garlic clove{1} (or use a #garlic press{}).

Pop the diced butternut onto a large #baking tray{}, drizzle with @oil{drizzle} and season with @salt{} and @pepper{}. Toss to coat then roast until golden and cooked through, ~{25-30%minutes}. Turn halfway through cooking. TIP: use two baking trays if you need to. Once cooked, remove from your oven.

Meanwhile, heat a drizzle of @oil{} in a large #frying pan{} over medium high heat. Add the onion and cook, stirring frequently, until soft and golden, ~{7-8%minutes}.

Add the @korma curry paste{50%g} and garlic to the pan with the onions and cook, stirring, for ~{1%minute}. Add the @coconut milk{200%ml}, @water{250%ml} and @vegetable stock powder{1%tbsp}. Add the @red split lentils{100%g}, stir and bring to a simmer. Reduce the heat and cover with a #lid{} (or some #foil{}) and cook until the lentils are soft, ~{20-25%minutes}. Check often to give a stir ensuring the lentils don't stick to the bottom of the pan.

While the lentils cook, trim the @spring onion{1}(trimmed and thinly sliced) and thinly slice. Once the lentils are cooked, add the @king prawns{150%g} and stir them through. Cover with a lid and simmer until the prawns are cooked through, ~{3-4%minutes}. IMPORTANT: The prawns are cooked when pink on the outside and opaque in the middle.

Add a splash of @water{} to the dahl if you need to. Stir two thirds of the roasted butternut through the dahl then divide between #bowls{} and top with the remaining roasted butternut and the spring onion. Enjoy!

> Looking for a quick and tasty midweek dinner option? This recipe takes about 40 minutes for a delicious and speedy meal.

> Nutrition: 563 kcal, 25g fat, 17g saturated fat, 60g carbs, 19g sugar, 29g protein, 3.2g sodium.